		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 11/30/1999 5:06:00 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=122&FN=Smithing&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=372286&TN=Bronze+vs+banded&CAT=Trade+Skills&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=372304&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">I don't think the whole college thing is a good analogy - I've got a better one.<P>Here in the real world, doctors get paid money hand over fist. Why? Not because there's anything that's incredibly difficult about medicine (as compared to any other advanced skill like theoretical physics). It's because of the time and money it takes to *become* a doctor.  When you pay your doctor, you aren't just paying him for his ability to take your temperature and check your reflexes - you are compensating him for all the time and money he spent to get that skill.<P>It's the same thing in EQ. Failure is part of the "cost of goods", friends. Expect to pay more for banded mantles and gauntlets, because they are harder to make. If you can find someone who is willing to sell them for the same price as the easier pieces, more power to you. But don't think it's your god-given right or anything, and don't think that people that charge you more are "gouging" you. <P>Why should Jewelers charge 3x cost of goods? Well, because they dumped on the order of 1000pp into their trade skill, while you were out adventuring and spending your money on armor, weapons, and other toys. I have nothing but respect for Jewelers, and they can charge whatever the market will bear.<P>As for me, when I get to where I can make banded armor (as opposed to #@$%@$ lanterns), I'm gonna charge what I think is a fair price for it. It'll be 1pp/AC for some items, but other items are gonna go for more, and I won't feel bad about charging it.<P>As for people who threaten to become Master Smiths themselves if the prices go up, I just have to laugh. *PLEASE* become master smiths. *PLEASE* dump a couple hundred plats into a trade skill, just to save a little money on a suit of banded armor. Come to Freeport, go through two zones every time you want to buy some Scaler molds. Sit in line at the forges for your turn to make metal bits. Watch your money evaporate before your eyes with every failure. Then, a couple dozen hours later, come back here and tell me how we are overcharging for our goods.<P>Sylven<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
