		<hr size="1">Ok, here we go, this is now going beyond the simple question of banded vs bronze and the pricing structure. <P>Forgive me for bringing this up but I could nor resist making this comment since people start bringing up real life analogies that are seriously flawed but never the less very interesting.<P>This is especially for you Trinsom, since you brought it up. First of all something about my background: I hold a university degree in International Management and I am working in the world of Multinational Companies. So I dare to say that I do have a fair share of economical background knowledge.<P>Trinsom your view of our economy is very simplistic and has little, if no, analogy in real life (no offense, only an observation). Read Sylven's post, he seems to have a good understanding of how our economy works.<P>Of course you are paying for "failures" in an endproduct. In real life you might refer to "failures" as overheads and even real failures as such of a company. Did you ever think about why you paid $49.99 (this is just an estimated number now)for your copy of EQ in the store. Lets asume the disc costs probably 10 cents, the packaging $5, the manual $5. (again estimated prices - don't quote me on that). Now according to what you are suggesting, Trinsom, you expect to pay around $20 for the copy (that is the raw material price with 100% margin). Now, where do the remaining $29.99 go? Some money goes to the store in their function as distributing channel and the rest goes to the company that made the game. Now, this is really very simplistic and only for the argument's sake.<P>With this money the company covers things like research and development, programming, administration, personnel costs etc. No company could function withour taking these costs into consideration. Every company invests a lot of money into producing its goods and the margin on the goods covers for these investments over a longer period of time.<P>Back to EQ: that is also why you pay for our "failures" and the money we invested into becoming a master of our trade. A trade skill is and should be, my opinion, a means to make some money.<P>Ok guys this is not intended to be a university paper on modern economics and I have to stress that I did simplify some aspects. But then again, this should only illustrate my point.<P>I remain with my opinion that people don't mind to pay my prices, which are not 1pp per AC and also cover some of my failures and expenses. Experience so far proves me right - just sold another 2 full sets of banded yesterday hehe  <IMG SRC="http://www.everlore.com/boards/EL/smile.gif"><P>A very interesting thread anyway...<P><P>------------------<BR>Aelven<BR>Druid on Innoruuk<BR>Master Smith<P><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
